question:
A 59-year-old overweight man (weight 87 kg; BMI 29.75) with sleep apnea was treated for stage III mantle cell lymphoma with systemic lymphadenopathy but no bone marrow involvement. Baseline liver–enzyme levels were normal, and hepatitis B and C serologic tests were negative. He received four cycles of R-DHAX (rituximab, dexamethasone, cytarabine, oxaliplatin) and achieved a complete metabolic response on PET–CT. Conditioning with BEAM (carmustine, etoposide, cytarabine, melphalan) was followed by autologous hematopoietic stem-cell transplantation on Day 0 (9.8×10^6 CD34+ cells per kg). Anti-infective prophylaxis included valacyclovir and fluconazole beginning on Day −7. Despite empirical piperacillin–tazobactam and voriconazole (then switched to caspofungin on Day +6) for persistent fever, no fungal infection was evident.

On Day +8, the patient became oligoanuric; examination showed hepatomegaly, ascites, fluid retention, and a 2-kg weight gain over 48 hours. Thrombocytopenia was refractory to transfusion.

On Day +9, laboratory studies revealed:  
• AST, 2914 IU/L (morning) rising to 5046 IU/L (evening) from 75 IU/L;  
• ALT, 1216 IU/L (from 45 IU/L);  
• Total bilirubin, 67 μmol/L (normal < 21 μmol/L);  
• Serum creatinine, 230 μmol/L;  
• Alkaline phosphatase initially normal, later twice the upper limit of normal;  
• INR progressively increasing; Factor V activity normal;  
• Plasminogen activator inhibitor-1, 51 UA/mL (normal < 16 UA/mL).  

Abdominal ultrasonography demonstrated hepatomegaly, ascites, and decreased portal-venous flow velocity. The patient’s weight had exceeded a 5% gain to 92 kg. He was diagnosed with hepatic veno-occlusive disease, admitted to the intensive care unit, and started on defibrotide (25 mg/kg/day).

What is the most likely cause of this patient's symptoms?
